Just because S lacks litigation competence in the placement order proceedings for example does not mean that she lacks subject matter competence (say, in relation to consent): Sheffield City Council v E [2004] EWHC 2808 (Fam) at [23] (“someone can have capacity for one purpose whilst simultaneously lacking capacity for another purpose”

 And see also [40] and [41]: ““[40] …the Official Solicitor is often engaged in litigation where questions arise in relation to each type of capacity. Not infrequently, for example, as he tells me, he agrees to act as guardian ad litem of a parent, the respondent to adoption proceedings, who lacks the capacity to litigate but who, on investigation, is nonetheless found to have capacity to give agreement to the making of an adoption order in accordance with section 16(1)(b)(i) of the Adoption Act 1976. [41] Correctly, in my judgment, the Official Solicitor accepts that the tests for what I will call "litigation capacity" and "subject-matter capacity" are not identical, and that an adult who lacks the capacity to litigate – lacks "litigation capacity" – may nonetheless have capacity with regard to the matters which are the subject of that litigation – "subject-matter capacity". One example is provided by the kind of adoption case to which I have just referred.”
		);
